Meet the landlords forced to bribe tenants to leave properties

'I even offered to pay the deposit on a new rental to get rid of them', one buy-to-let investor said

By Rachel Mortimer and Melissa Lawford 11 July 2021 5:00am

Landlords have resorted to paying troublesome tenants and writing off arrears in a bid to regain control of their properties.

Faced with a huge backlog of evictions in the courts, many desperate landlords have cut their losses and agreed financial deals.

A north London letting agent, who asked to remain anonymous, said: We have an open case with a tenant who stopped paying rent six months ago. He is 6,500 in arrears. I have offered him 1,000 and will write off the arrears, if he will just give us back the property.

One landlord was willing to wipe more than 50,000 in arrears accrued by a tenant claiming rent did not need to be paid throughout the pandemic, despite the debts dating to before the crisis. After a mediation process, the landlord recovered 45,000 and took a financial hit of 5,000 to regain possession of his property without a protracted process through the courts.

Emergency rules in place for most of last year meant landlords were required to give six months notice of an eviction. At the end of May this year this dropped to four months, to remain in place until September, and bailiff evictions resumed.

Courts will buckle under the lockdown backlog and Covid arrears cases

It means if a tenant was served a notice in May, they cannot be evicted until the beginning of December.

While exceptions apply in extreme circumstances, such as fraud, domestic abuse and severe rental arrears, vast legal bottlenecks mean this does not always apply in practice.

The letting agent added: The eviction process is the biggest factor. It was always lengthy, but since Covid it has become so much worse and you dont know where you stand.

Sherrelle Collman, of adviser Caridon Landlord Solutions, said: Many landlords are so desperate now that they are willing to cut their losses and write off arrears just to gain vacant possession and avoid a lengthy and expensive court process.

The eviction ban has prevented at least 30k evictions

A recent report by the University of York found landlords who were worried that increasingly restrictive regulations would hamper eviction had paid problematic tenants to leave.

Dr Julie Rugg, author of the report, said the practice most often applied in cases of antisocial tenants or where huge arrears had accumulated. A landlord wont ask a good tenant to leave, so payments like this can represent exhaustion on the landlords part.

Jeff Smith, 58, is a landlord with around 200 tenants. Speaking using a pseudonym, he said: I have two tenants that I have offered to pay to leave. One was 20,000 in arrears, the other was 12,000 in arrears, and I offered to find them each a place to live and pay the first months rent and the deposit. I was going to write off their arrears.

Mr Smith expected to pay 2,000 to 2,500 on each case to cover the costs, but in both instances his offer was rejected. They wanted to be rehoused by the council and they were told to wait for the bailiffs.

Tenants who are on benefits will not take cash incentives because they are likely to invalidate their housing applications with local councils. If a tenant is in receipt of benefits, offering an incentive to leave is a problem because the council then deems them intentionally homeless, said Mr Smith.

Paul Shamplina, founder of Landlord Action, an eviction service, said: If a landlord is faced with choosing an eviction process, which could take up to 14 months, or writing off existing arrears but re-letting the property much sooner, the landlord has to weigh up which makes most financial sense and is the least stressful.

The private rental sector faces a 360m black hole of arrears accumulated since the pandemic began last year, according to the debt charity StepChange. The National Residential Landlords Association, a trade body, found almost a third of tenants in arrears owed 1,000 or more.

Paul Turner, a 56-year-old landlord, was left with outstanding arrears of more than 26,000 after an arduous battle with a tenant who stopped paying rent in 2019. After more than a year of failed negotiations a judge ordered the tenant to vacate the property in May, but Mr Turner, who also spoke using a pseudonym, has still not received any of the money owed.

He said: It is literally daylight robbery. I have had to take a sabbatical from work just to sort it out.
